  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "More than memory and learning or consciousness, intelligence is a critical distinction between humans, non-human animals and the emerging more or less intelligent embodiments of computational Artificial Intelligence (AI) and OI (Figure 1).",
    "The rise of AI has started a discussion about when to consider these systems intelligent.",
    "Laskar (2023) argues that genuine machine intelligence does not simply rely on traditional machine learning or neural networks but on causal learning and inference algorithms.",
    "To develop truly intelligent machines, it is imperative to teach them how to interact with the world, moving beyond pattern recognition to understanding causal relationships.",
    "True machine intelligence is represented by causal models of the world, not mere statistical models."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "Laskar (2023) argues that genuine machine intelligence does not simply rely on traditional machine learning or neural networks but on causal learning and inference algorithms."
